        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat(gateway): add device.pair.setupCode RPC for connect QR",
        "body": "## Summary\r\n\r\nPart of #94661 (wizard RPC parity for non-terminal clients).\r\n\r\nThe OpenClaw mobile/companion app scans a **pairing setup code** to connect to the gateway. The gateway already *accepts* such clients (the setup-code mobile bootstrap seam) and exposes pairing **approval** RPCs (`node.pair.*`, `device.pair.*`), but the setup code + connect QR could only be **produced** by the `openclaw qr` CLI, which renders ASCII to stdout. A companion / GUI / Control UI driving onboarding had no way to **display** the connect QR.\r\n\r\nThis adds a `device.pair.setupCode` gateway method that returns the setup code and a QR data URL so non-terminal clients can show the connect QR. It reuses the exact helpers `openclaw qr` already uses.\r\n\r\n> Note: channel-login QR (e.g. WhatsApp) is a separate concern and already has a gateway RPC (`web.login.start` / `web.login.wait` return `qrDataUrl`). This PR is specifically the **device/connection** setup-code QR.\r\n\r\n## How it works\r\n\r\n- New method `device.pair.setupCode` (scope `operator.admin`, `advertise: false`).\r\n- Reuses `resolvePairingSetupFromConfig` + `encodePairingSetupCode` (`src/pairing/setup-code.ts`) and `renderQrPngDataUrl` (`src/media/qr-image.ts`).\r\n- Returns `{ setupCode, qrDataUrl?, gatewayUrl, auth, urlSource }`. `includeQr: false` skips QR rendering, and an oversized QR (beyond the result schema's 16 KB cap) is omitted so the response always validates — the client can render the QR from `setupCode`.\r\n- Protocol schema added in `packages/gateway-protocol` (params + result), with a param validator.\r\n\r\n## Security\r\n\r\n- Scoped **`operator.admin`** and **not advertised**. The embedded setup code mints a short-lived bootstrap token that hands off broad operator scopes (`read` / `write` / `approvals` / `talk.secrets`), so the method must require the highest operator scope — which the companion that drives onboarding already holds (the `wizard.*` methods it uses are all `operator.admin`). Gating only at `operator.pairing` would let a narrower caller mint a broader grant.\r\n- `auth` is a **label only** (`\"token\"` | `\"password\"`) — the raw gateway credential and the bootstrap token are never returned as response fields. A regression test asserts the bootstrap token never appears as a field.\r\n\r\n## Change type\r\n\r\n- [x] Feature (gateway protocol; additive)\r\n\r\n## Scope\r\n\r\n- [x] Gateway / orchestration\r\n- [x] Auth / tokens\r\n- [x] API / contracts (additive)\r\n- [x] UI / DX\r\n\r\n## Real behavior proof\r\n\r\nBehavior addressed: a gateway RPC now returns the device-pairing setup code + connect QR data URL so non-terminal clients can display it; previously only the `openclaw qr` CLI could render it (ASCII to stdout).\r\nReal environment tested: local OpenClaw worktree on latest `main` (Windows).\r\nExact steps or command run after this patch: `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs run src/gateway/server-methods/device-pair-setup.test.ts`; descriptor-drift / registry guards `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs run src/gateway/server-startup-plugins.test.ts src/gateway/server-startup-post-attach.test.ts src/gateway/server-methods.control-plane-rate-limit.test.ts`; `pnpm tsgo:core`; `pnpm tsgo:core:test`; oxlint + oxfmt on touched files.\r\nEvidence after fix: handler tests pass (5 cases incl. \"returns only an auth label\" and \"bootstrap token never appears as a field\"); descriptor-drift guards pass (172 tests) confirming the new descriptor↔handler wiring is consistent; `tsgo:core` and `tsgo:core:test` exit 0; lint and format clean.\r\nObserved result after fix: `device.pair.setupCode` responds `{ setupCode, qrDataUrl, gatewayUrl, auth: \"token\"|\"password\", urlSource }`; on resolve failure it returns an INVALID_REQUEST error; unknown params are rejected before any pairing helper runs.\r\nWhat was not tested: live scan-to-connect from a physical iOS/Windows app (companion rendering lands separately), and full-repo `pnpm check` / `pnpm test`.\r\n\r\n## Compatibility\r\n\r\n- Backward compatible? Yes — additive method; existing clients unaffected.\r\n- Config/env changes? No. Migration needed? No.\r\n\r\nAI-assisted: Yes.\r\n",
